## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow.

In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone (`SYSLIB0006`). You must switch to cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task.Run replaces manual Thread creation
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws TimeoutException if the timeout expires
            return task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Better version — cooperative cancellation (recommended)

The above is a 1:1 port, but the work still runs after timeout. For *actual* cancellation, the work must cooperate:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}

// Caller must cooperate:
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If the delegate ignores the token, it keeps running after timeout. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** | It holds timer resources. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Let it propagate; only catch at the orchestration boundary (as shown above). |
| **`Thread.Sleep` won't respond to cancellation** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `Task.Delay(ms, token)`. |
| **Blocking I/O won't cancel** | Synchronous `socket.Read()` etc. won't check the token. Use async overloads that accept `CancellationToken`. |

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Why it fails in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `cts.Cancel()` / `cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |

The fundamental shift: **.NET Framework could forcibly kill a thread mid-execution; .NET 8 cannot.** Your code must voluntarily check for cancellation at regular intervals.
